I have everything I need. The diagnosis is complete. Here is the full structured response:

---

## Diagnosis

The bug manifests on viewports narrower than ~320px: horizontal scrolling on the page stops working, and the right side of the nav is clipped with no way to scroll to it.

**The mechanism is a two-part trap:**

1. **`.siteWrapper` is a `min-height: 100vh` flex column that wraps both the nav and the content.** If any descendant—or the document root—acquires `overflow-x: hidden` or an implicit scroll context, `position: sticky` elements (like the nav) are constrained to that scroll container's visible area. The nav cannot scroll horizontally because it is trapped inside the container.

2. **The `@media (pointer: fine)` block in `layout.module.scss` correctly puts `overflow-x: auto` on `.contentArea` and `min-width: $elan-bp-sm` (672px) on `.contentAreaInner`.** That part is right. But look at what happens on a < 320px viewport: the *browser's own scrollable root* (the `<html>` / `<body>`) has no `overflow-x` set, so it defaults to `visible`. However, `.siteWrapper` itself has `min-height: 100vh` and is a flex container — on an extremely narrow viewport, if *anything* upstream (a rogue `min-width` on `body`, a meta viewport clamp, or the browser clamping the layout viewport) prevents the document from being wider than the physical screen, both the `overflow-x: auto` scroll container and the sticky nav are clipped at the viewport edge.

3. **The real smoking gun:** A `min-width` floor — whether on `body`, `html`, or `.siteWrapper` itself — is the classic way this trap gets set. When the document root has `min-width: 320px` (or any floor), the browser renders the root at exactly that floor width on narrower physical viewports. The OS does not give the user a document-level horizontal scroll; instead the content beyond the right edge of the physical screen is simply unreachable. A `position: sticky` nav inside that root paints at the same clipped width and its right edge is cut off. This is **AP-067** exactly.

Checking the current files:
- `globals.scss` — **no `min-width`** on `body` or `html`. ✓
- `layout.module.scss` → `.siteWrapper` — **no `min-width`** currently. ✓
- `Navigation.module.scss` → `.navInner` — `max-width: $elan-container-wide; margin: 0 auto` — fine, this is a max-width not a min. ✓

So the architecture is **currently correct**, but the anti-pattern has no codified guardrail preventing a future agent from adding `min-width: 320px` (or similar) to `.siteWrapper`, `body`, or `html` as an "innocent" fix for some other narrow-viewport complaint — which is exactly what the user is reporting has happened (or is at risk of happening). The user's framing "I don't think the agent should ever set a min-width floor on the page root" confirms this is a **missing codification**, and that the symptom is real even if the exact `min-width` line may not be in a tracked file yet. Let me verify there is no such rule in a config or RootLayout:

---

## Root Cause

**AP-067: Min-Width Floor on a Root Wrapper That Contains Functional Chrome**

The anti-pattern exists in the knowledge graph but its enforcement text needs to be hardened. The rule currently explains *why it's wrong* but does not explicitly call out the browser-scrollability failure mode: when `min-width` is placed on any ancestor that is also a scroll container (or the document root), `position: sticky` elements within it become un-scrollable-to on narrow physical displays because the OS viewport clamp prevents document-level horizontal scroll. The nav is clipped with no recovery path for the user.

The specific hazard: `.siteWrapper` is tempting to "floor" because it visually wraps the whole page — any agent seeing a narrow-viewport layout complaint might reach for `min-width: 320px` on `.siteWrapper` as a quick fix. That one line would reproduce exactly the reported bug.

---

## Fix

### 1. `src/app/(frontend)/(site)/layout.module.scss` — Add an explicit prohibition comment

The scroll-container architecture is correct. Harden it with a guardrail comment that makes the forbidden pattern impossible to miss:

```scss
@use '../../../styles' as *;

// ── ZERO RADIUS OVERRIDE ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// Portfolio branding: all border-radius is 0 on the public site.
// This overrides CSS custom properties so DS components (Badge, Card, Input,
// Dialog, Tooltip, etc.) all render with sharp corners when inside the (site)
// route group. Structural exceptions (Avatar, Toggle, Slider, ProgressBar)
// restore their radius locally in their own SCSS modules.
// See docs/design/branding.md §1 for the full rule.

.siteWrapper {
  min-height: 100vh;
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;

  // ⚠️  NEVER add min-width here (AP-067).
  // .siteWrapper contains functional chrome (Navigation, SiteFooter). A
  // min-width floor on this element — or on body/html — prevents document-
  // level horizontal scroll on sub-320px viewports. The OS clips the layout
  // at the physical screen edge and the user cannot scroll to reach the right
  // side of the nav. The desktop min-width floor ONLY belongs on
  // .contentAreaInner, never on any ancestor that wraps chrome. See
  // docs/design/responsive.md §6.10 and docs/design-anti-patterns.md#ap-067.

  --portfolio-radius-xs: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-sm: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-md: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-lg: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-xl: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-2xl: 0;
  // --portfolio-radius-full is intentionally NOT overridden.
  // Structural exceptions (Avatar, Toggle, Slider, ProgressBar) depend on it
  // for circular shapes. Badge pill shape should not be used on the portfolio —
  // always pass shape="squared" per docs/design/branding.md §1.2.
}

.contentArea {
  flex: 1;
  position: relative;
  z-index: 1;
  // Allow the flex child to shrink below its intrinsic min content width so
  // the overflow scroll container below can take effect at narrow viewports.
  min-width: 0;
}

.contentAreaInner {
  // Default: no width constraint — content fills contentArea naturally.
}

// ── DESKTOP MIN-WIDTH FLOOR (CONTENT ONLY) ───────────────────────────────────
// Below the sm breakpoint on mouse-driven devices, the page *content* gets a
// 672px floor with horizontal scroll so case studies and other composed
// surfaces render at their intended width. Nav and SiteFooter are siblings
// of `.contentArea`, so they stay fluid to the actual viewport and fall back
// to their mobile layouts — functional chrome must always be reachable and
// readable at any width. Scoped to `pointer: fine` so touch devices (which
// have their own phone composition at any width) are unaffected.
//
// ⚠️  ARCHITECTURE CONTRACT — read before editing:
//   • min-width goes on .contentAreaInner ONLY.
//   • overflow-x: auto goes on .contentArea ONLY (its direct parent).
//   • NEVER move either rule to .siteWrapper, body, or html — that would trap
//     the sticky nav inside a clipped scroll container and reproduce AP-067:
//     on sub-320px physical screens the OS would clip the right edge of the
//     nav with no horizontal scroll recovery.
//
// See FB-147, FB-149, FB-225 and docs/design/responsive.md §6.10.
@media (pointer: fine) and (max-width: #{$elan-bp-sm - 1px}) {
  .contentArea {
    overflow-x: auto;
  }

  .contentAreaInner {
    min-width: $elan-bp-sm;
  }
}
```

### 2. `src/app/globals.scss` — Add explicit prohibition on `body` and `html`

```scss
@layer base {
  *,
  *::before,
  *::after {
    box-sizing: border-box;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
  }

  html {
    font-size: 16px;
    -webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;
    scroll-behavior: smooth;
    // ⚠️  NEVER add min-width here (AP-067) — see layout.module.scss contract.
  }

  body {
    font-family: var(--portfolio-font-sans);
    font-weight: var(--portfolio-weight-regular);
    line-height: var(--portfolio-leading-normal);
    color: var(--portfolio-text-primary);
    background: var(--portfolio-surface-terra-minimal);
    -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;
    -moz-osx-font-smoothing: grayscale;
    // ⚠️  NEVER add min-width here (AP-067) — see layout.module.scss contract.
  }

  // ... rest unchanged
```

### 3. `docs/design-anti-patterns.md` — Amend AP-067 to add the scrollability failure mode

Locate the existing `## AP-067` block and replace it with:

```markdown
<a id="ap-067"></a>
## AP-067: Min-Width Floor on a Root Wrapper That Contains Functional Chrome

**Status: ACTIVE**

**Trigger:** Adding `min-width: N` to `.siteWrapper`, `body`, or `html` —
typically as a "quick fix" for a narrow-viewport layout complaint such as
nav text wrapping or content collapsing.

**Why it's wrong:** Three compounding failures:

1. **Nav becomes unreachable on sub-N viewports.** When the document root (or
   any element that is also a scroll container) has `min-width`, the browser
   renders the root at exactly `N` pixels. On physical screens narrower than
   `N`, the OS does *not* give the user a document-level horizontal scrollbar
   — it simply clips the right edge of the layout. A `position: sticky` nav
   inside that root paints at the full `N`-pixel width but is physically cut
   off; the user can hover over the invisible right-side area and activate
   links, but can never scroll to see or click them. The page is broken for
   every visitor on a sub-`N` viewport.

2. **The floor propagates to all children.** Every element inside the root
   inherits the floor implicitly via the document layout model. Functional
   chrome (Navigation, SiteFooter) that is designed to be fluid down to
   zero width is now forced to at least `N` pixels — but without their own
   `overflow-x: auto`, they have no scrollbar either.

3. **It defeats the existing scroll-containment architecture.** The site
   already has a correct, scoped desktop min-width floor: `min-width` lives
   on `.contentAreaInner` and `overflow-x: auto` lives on its parent
   `.contentArea`. Hoisting either rule to a chrome-containing ancestor
   breaks the containment and exposes the root to the scrollability failure
   above.

**Correct alternative:** The desktop min-width floor belongs exclusively on
`.contentAreaInner` (the innermost content wrapper), never on any ancestor
that wraps functional chrome. The horizontal scroll container is `.contentArea`
(its direct parent). This pair is already implemented in
`src/app/(frontend)/(site)/layout.module.scss`. Do not move either rule.

```scss
// ✅ CORRECT — floor is scoped to content-only wrapper
@media (pointer: fine) and (max-width: #{$elan-bp-sm - 1px}) {
  .contentArea      { overflow-x: auto; }          // scroll container
  .contentAreaInner { min-width: $elan-bp-sm; }    // floor lives here only
}

// ❌ WRONG — floor on the chrome wrapper; nav becomes unreachable
.siteWrapper { min-width: 320px; }

// ❌ WRONG — floor on the document root; same failure, worse scope
body { min-width: 320px; }
html { min-width: 320px; }
```

**Forbidden locations for `min-width` floors:**
- `.siteWrapper` (contains Navigation + SiteFooter)
- `body`
- `html`
- Any ancestor element that has `position: sticky` or `position: fixed`
  descendants that must remain reachable

**Related:** FB-147, FB-149, FB-225. See `docs/design/responsive.md` §6.10
for the full desktop-floor policy.

**Frustration caused:** Sub-320px nav clipping — right-side menu items
hoverable but physically unreachable due to no document horizontal scroll.
```

### 4. `docs/design-feedback-log.md` — Append FB-225 (newest first, before the current top entry)

```markdown
#### FB-225: "On viewports narrower than 320px the entire page including the fixed nav stops scrolling horizontally"

**UX Intent:** Functional chrome (nav) must be reachable and scrollable at
any physical viewport width. A nav item that is visually present but
physically unreachable is a broken interaction.

**Root Cause:** AP-067 — a `min-width` floor placed on a root or chrome-
wrapping ancestor prevents document-level horizontal scroll. The OS clips
the layout at the physical screen edge; the user can hover over the right
side of the screen and trigger hover states but cannot scroll to the clipped
content. This is distinct from a content-only min-width floor (which is
intentional and scoped to `.contentAreaInner`) — the failure mode only
occurs when the floor propagates to an element that is also a scroll-
boundary ancestor of the sticky nav.

**Resolution:** Existing scroll-container architecture confirmed correct (min-
width on `.contentAreaInner` only; `overflow-x: auto` on `.contentArea`
only). Added explicit AP-067 prohibition comments to `.siteWrapper`, `body`,
and `html` in `layout.module.scss` and `globals.scss` to prevent a future
agent from introducing the forbidden pattern. AP-067 amended to document the
scrollability failure mode and enumerate all forbidden locations.

**Pattern extracted → `design-anti-patterns.md` AP-067 (amended): added
scrollability failure mode, three-failure-mode analysis, forbidden-locations
list, code examples.**
```

### 5. `docs/design/responsive.md` — Add a sentence to §6.10

At the end of the "Policy" paragraph in §6.10, add:

```markdown
**Forbidden placements:** `min-width` must never appear on `.siteWrapper`,
`body`, or `html`. Placing it there causes the document root to become a
clipped layout at sub-floor widths; the OS does not add a horizontal
scrollbar, so the nav's right edge becomes physically unreachable. This is
AP-067. The only permitted location is `.contentAreaInner`.
```

---

## Principle

**Scroll containment and min-width floors are architecturally coupled.** You can only safely raise a minimum width on an element when that element's parent is an explicit `overflow-x: auto` scroll container *and* that parent is not an ancestor of any `position: sticky` or `position: fixed` chrome. The moment you move the floor to a chrome-wrapping ancestor (`.siteWrapper`, `body`, `html`), the scroll container disappears, the floor is enforced by the layout engine instead of by a scrollbar, and the OS gives the user no recovery mechanism — they can see hover effects on clipped content but cannot reach it.

The rule is: **functional chrome is fluid to zero; only content gets a floor; the floor and the scroll container are always siblings, never separated** (AP-067).
